AWS Resource Access Manager (AWS RAM) is the service you’re referring to — it allows you to securely share AWS resources across accounts, organizational units (OUs), or your entire AWS Organization without duplicating them. This is especially useful in multi‑account setups where networking or security resources need to be centrally managed but consumed by multiple teams.

🔑 What AWS RAM Does
Cross‑Account Sharing: Share resources with other AWS accounts, OUs, or your whole Organization.
Granular Permissions: Use AWS‑managed or customer‑managed permissions to control access.
Supported Resources: Includes VPC subnets, Transit Gateways, Route 53 Resolver rules, License Manager configs, Network Firewall policies, Aurora DB clusters, EC2 Image Builder components, Outposts, and more.
Visibility & Auditing: Integrated with CloudWatch and CloudTrail for monitoring and compliance.

⚙️ How Resource Sharing Works
Owner Account: Creates and manages the resource (e.g., a Transit Gateway).
Resource Share: Owner defines which accounts/OUs can use the resource.
Consumer Accounts: Can use the resource (e.g., launch EC2 instances into shared subnets) but cannot modify or delete it.
Control: Owner retains full control while consumers gain usage rights.

✅ Benefits
Reduce Operational Overhead: Create once, share many times — no duplication across accounts.
Consistency: Apply a single set of policies and permissions instead of replicating them everywhere.
Security: Enforce least‑privilege access with managed permissions.
Auditability: Track usage and access via CloudTrail logs.

🚀 Example Scenario
Imagine you have a central networking account in your AWS Organization:
Networking team manages VPCs and Transit Gateways.
Application teams in separate accounts need to launch workloads into those subnets.
Instead of duplicating VPCs in each account, you use AWS RAM to share subnets and Transit Gateway.
Application teams can deploy workloads seamlessly, while networking retains control.
